            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Thompson is a product of Midwestern pragmatism, a sensibility she carries like a well-worn tool. Raised in suburban Ohio by a chemical engineer father and a meticulous homemaker mother, she learned early that success was a matter of process and precision. She traded the flat horizons of home for the California coast, earning her Industrial Engineering degree from Cal Poly San Luis Obispo, where the \"learn by doing\" ethos resonated with her practical nature.\n\nShe arrived in the Bay Area in the late 1990s, just as the first dot-com bubble was inflating. While her peers chased stock options in nascent tech startups, Heather found a steady, tangible career in manufacturing. Her methodical ascent from junior engineer to Quality Assurance Director was built on a reputation for being unflappable and thorough. She weathered the dot-com bust and the 2008 recession by ensuring the medical devices her company produced were flawless, a responsibility she found deeply meaningful. A key turning point was her divorce five years ago. The split from her husband, a marketing executive who craved the city\u2019s vibrant social scene, was amicable but definitive. It solidified her identity as an independent woman who valued stability over spectacle.\n\nNow an empty-nester with her son away at college, Heather\u2019s life is a study in organized routine. Her day begins before dawn in her modest Outer Sunset home, a quiet sanctuary she chose for its remove from the city\u2019s frantic core. The 14.5-mile commute in her reliable sedan down I-280 to a South San Francisco manufacturing plant is a quiet ritual of coffee and podcasts. After a day spent overseeing protocols and signing off on production runs, she returns to the fog-laced streets of her neighborhood. She finds comfort in the city\u2019s permanence\u2014the chill of the ocean air during a walk along Ocean Beach, the consistent quality of the sourdough at her local bakery.\n\nHer social life consists of a small, loyal circle of friends, mostly colleagues and old neighbors. Heather\u2019s aspirations are not grand, but deeply felt. She dreams of taking a solo trip to Scandinavia to study minimalist design, and perhaps finding a companion who shares her appreciation for a quiet, well-ordered life. She is a woman content in the world she has built, a testament to quality control applied not just to products, but to a life itself."
